JOHANNESBURG &#8211; South Africa&#8217;s rand followed Asian currencies lower on Monday ahead of Donald Trump&#8217;s presidential inauguration and comments from Federal Reserve officials that may provide clarity on the outlook for U.S. policies and the dollar.* At 09:00, rand 0.35 percent softer at 13.5650/dlr.* NKC African Economics, in a research note, says rand expected to trade between 13.40 and 13.70/dollar for the session.* &#8220;The election of Republican Donald Trump as the next U.S. president has caused much uncertainty over future U.S. policy, which appears to have hurt emerging market sentiment in the immediate aftermath of the U.S. election,&#8221; NKC said.* In fixed income, government bonds little changed with the yield for the benchmark instrument due in 2026 ZAR186= down half a basis point to 8.665%.* Stocks open lower, also following Asian markets, with the benchmark Top-40 index 0.43% lower at 45,871.